docs.abstract: Readers make pitches for the city it should pick for its second headquarters. But a Seattle reader cautions, “Be careful what you wish for.”
docs.snippet: Readers make pitches for the city it should pick for its second headquarters. But a Seattle reader cautions, “Be careful what you wish for.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Amazon is often promoting the idea of improving the world. Therefore its second headquarters should do that. Knowing that it is a game changer, Amazon should go to a Rust Belt city and forever alter the economy of the region. Take a good look at Pittsburgh or Cleveland. Both have had a renaissance and offer lovely downtowns, beautiful architecture, great waterfronts, beautiful parks, treelined streets, excellent cultural amenities, great public transportation and pro sports teams. Even better, they have great colleges and medical facilities.

headline.print_headline: To Woo Amazon, Nothing’s Too Weird

docs.abstract: Why Amazon’s new headquarters decision should be an act of patriotism.
docs.snippet: Why Amazon’s new headquarters decision should be an act of patriotism.
docs.lead_paragraph: A couple of interesting things are happening with the massive companies that rule our online lives. First, the lords of Silicon Valley face political headwinds. There is tech-company skepticism on the populist right, the anti-corporate left and the good-government center. There is talk of trustbusting and utility-style regulation from Steve Bannon as well as Bernie Sanders. There is a palpable feeling, as Ben Smith of Buzzfeed wrote last week, that the online giants’ “golden age” of political immunity is ending, and that it might be “normal politics, normal regulation” from here on out.

headline.main: Meet Me in St. Louis, Bezos
headline.print_headline: Meet Me In St. Louis, Bezos

docs.abstract: Amazon is on the forefront of automation, finding new ways of getting robots to do the work once handled by human employees.
docs.snippet: Amazon is on the forefront of automation, finding new ways of getting robots to do the work once handled by human employees.
docs.lead_paragraph: FLORENCE, N.J. — Nissa Scott started working at the cavernous Amazon warehouse in southern New Jersey late last year, stacking plastic bins the size of small ottomans. It was not, she says, the most stimulating activity. And lifting the bins, which often weigh 25 pounds each, was also tiring over 10-hour shifts.

headline.main: As Amazon Pushes Forward With Robots, Workers Find New Roles
